07219nam a22008535i 9789633864401DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20212021hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2021039476  a9789633864401  a(DE-B1597)633194  a(OCoLC)1291315926  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU00aGN36.E852 4aGN36.E852bS73 2021 7aSOC0020102bisacsh00aStaged Otherness :bEthnic Shows in Central and Eastern Europe, 1850-1939 /ced. by Dagnosław Demski, Dominika Czarnecka. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (460 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: From Western to Peripheral Voices -- tI. European versus Indigenous Agency -- t2. The Hagenbeck Ethnic Shows: Recruitment, Organization, and Academic and Popular Responses -- t3. A Brief History of Staging Somali Ethnographic Performing Troupes in Europe, 1885-1930 -- t4. "Wild Chamacoco" and the Czechs: The Double-Edged Ethnographic Show of Vojtěch Frič, 1908-9 -- t5. Why Hidden Ears Matter: On Kalintsov's Samoyed Exhibition in Vienna, 1882 -- tII. Performing the Ethnographic Other -- t6. The (Ethno-)Drama of Exoticism: Ethnic Shows as a Medium -- t7. How Do These "Exotic" Bodies Move? Ethnographic Shows and Constructing Otherness in the Polish-Language Press, 1880-1914 -- t8. The World of Creation: Press Accounts of Ethnographic Shows in Circus Performances in Upper Silesia -- tIII. Across Local Contexts -- t9. Racialized Performance and the Construction of Slovene Whiteness: Ethnographic Shows and Circus Acts on the Habsburg Periphery, 1880-1914 -- t10. A Century of Elision? Ethnic Shows in Saint Petersburg and Moscow, 1879-1914 -- t11. "When Winter Arrives, the Sinhalese Go Back to Ceylon and Their Elephants Go to Hamburg": Hagenbeck's Sinhalese Caravans and Ethnographic Imagery in the Polish Press during the Partition Era -- t12. The Call of the Wild: A Sociological Sketch of Buffalo Bill's Wild West in Banat and Transylvania -- t13. "Staged Otherness" in Saint Petersburg -- tEpilogue -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe cultural phenomenon of exhibiting non-European people in front of the European audiences in the 19th and 20th century was concentrated in the metropolises in the western part of the continent. Nevertheless, traveling ethnic troupes and temporary exhibitions of non-European humans took place also in territories located to the east of the Oder river and Austria. The contributors to this edited volume present practices of ethnographic shows in Russia, Poland, Czechia, Slovenia, Hungary, Germany, Romania, and Austria and discuss the reactions of local audiences. The essays offer critical arguments to rethink narratives of cultural encounters in the context of ethnic shows. By demonstrating the many ways in which the western models and customs were reshaped, developed, and contested in Central and Eastern European contexts, the authors argue that the dominant way of characterizing these performances as "human zoos" is too narrow. The contributors had to tackle the difficult task of finding traces other than faint copies of official press releases by the tour organizers. The original source material was drawn from local archives, museums, and newspapers of the discussed period. A unique feature of the volume is the rich amount of images that complement every single case study of ethnic shows.  afunded by Opening the Future  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, v